\begin_layout Section
Scattering transform on the wavelet scalogram
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Shepard pitch spiral
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\log_{2}\lambda_{1}=\lfloor\log_{2}\lambda_{1}\rfloor+\lbrace\log_{2}\lambda_{1}\rbrace
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The integer part 
\begin_inset Formula $\lfloor\log_{2}\lambda_{1}\rfloor$
\end_inset

 is related to pitch height, whereas the fractional part 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\log_{2}\lambda_{1}\}$
\end_inset

 is related to pitch chroma.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Spiral wavelet
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Psi_{\lambda_{2}}(t,\lambda_{1})=\psi_{\alpha}(t)\times\psi_{\beta}(\log_{2}\lambda_{1})\times\psi_{\gamma}(\lfloor\log_{2}\lambda_{1}\rfloor)
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x_{2}(t,\lambda_{1},\lambda_{2})=\vert x_{1}\ast\Psi_{\lambda_{2}}\vert(t,\lambda_{1})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Capturing pitch chroma and pitch height velocities
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Varying pitch chroma: the Shepard-Risset glissando
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Shepard tones
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A Shepard tone is a sum of sine waves which are one octave apart:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x(t)=\sum_{k=0}^{K-1}\sin(2\pi2^{k}f_{0}t)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Shepard tones do not have a specifitch pitch height ; instead, they are
 entirely determined by their pitch chroma.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Shepard tones are self-similar: 
\begin_inset Formula $x(2t)\approx x(t)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Shepard-Risset glissando
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A Shepard-Risset glissando is built by playing a Shepard tone at a tape
 speed that increases exponentially.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
This corresponds to a uniform motion of the pitch chroma.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Shepard-Risset glissandi are periodic because of the circularity of chromas.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x_{\tau}(t)=x\left(\tau(t)\right)
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tau=\dfrac{}{V_{\mathrm{chroma}}}\dfrac{T_{\mathrm{chroma}}}{\log2}2^{t/T_{\mathrm{chroma}}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\mathrm{chroma}}$
\end_inset

 is the duration of a full octave rise in pitch chroma.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Shepard-Risset glissando yields a simple particular case of a result
 proven by Joakim And√©n on joint time-frequency characterization of chirps:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x_{2,\tau}(t,\lambda_{1},\lambda_{2})\propto\widehat{\psi}\left(-\dfrac{\beta\log2}{\alpha T_{\mathrm{chroma}}}\right)
\]

\end_inset

In other words, 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}$
\end_inset

 is maximal when the slope 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha/\beta$
\end_inset

 is equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\log2/T_{\mathrm{chroma}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Varying pitch height: the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Shepard arpeggio
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x_{g}(t)=\sum_{k=1}^{K}2^{k}g\left(\dfrac{t}{T_{\mathrm{height}}}-k\right)\sin(2\pi2^{k}f_{0}t)
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $T_{\mathrm{height}}$
\end_inset

 is the duration of a full octave rise in pitch height.
 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is a zero-centered bump function ; we have chosen a standard Gaussian in
 our experiments.
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x_{2,g}(t,\lambda_{1},\lambda_{2})\propto g\left(\dfrac{T_{\text{\mathrm{height}}}+\frac{\gamma}{\beta}}{\alpha T_{\mathrm{height}}}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

